{          Everything You Need to Know About 2C Auctions          }
^-|ht|c|fp||cp|8|AT|^B@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|Everyone loves to pick up a big hand. And when the big hand is clearly strong enough to open 2@C, that is better still. However, sometimes the decision as to whether or not you should open 2@C is far from obvious. Additionally, after a 2@C opening bid followed by responder's 2@D waiting bid, the partnership is very much in the dark.|
PG| ***** 1 ***** |


at|

Responder knows absolutely nothing about opener's distribution at this point. Meanwhile, not only does opener know nothing about responder's distribution, he also has absolutely no idea about the strength of responder's hand. This is certainly not a recipe for success. So auctions involving 2@C openers are frequently far from trivial.|
PG| ***** 2 ***** |


HT|i|cs|2|3d|5|at|^b  {|ih|pSS A K Q T 7 5 2 H 5 D A K 3 C 7 6|at|}|ht|i|va|2|lb|*yShould you open this hand 2C?^^y|ht|i|va|2|at|^k@2Some people would say this hand has a mere 16 HCP. Technically speaking, one can't disagree. But let's think. With spades as trump, you expect to take 7 spade tricks and 2 diamond tricks with no problem. Yes, spades could split badly. Anything could happen. But if partner has a doubleton diamond and a couple of spades, you will easily make 4@S. |
PG| ***** 4 ***** |


ht|n|va|2|AT|^b@2
The bottom line is that this is a 2@C opener. You don't need a lot from partner to make a slam. The @CAK and @DQ would suffice. Picture the following: Say you open 1@S and partner bids 1NT, their most likely bid. I assume you would jump to 4@S. You don't want to get involved with a phony jump shift. How would you feel if partner really liked diamonds and kept supporting that suit and you ended up not playing in spades? |
PG| ***** 5 ***** |


AT|

Over 4@S partner will pass with many hands where you can make a slam. So open 2@C. Keep bidding your spades over and over again. You will end up in 4@S if partner is weak. You have an excellent chance to make that no matter how weak partner is. There is no reason not to open 2@C. You have 4 quick tricks. 'Quick tricks' are the number of tricks you will take on the first 2 rounds of each suit. So the @SAK and @DAK count as 4 quick tricks. |
PG| ***** 6 ***** |


AT|

I am going to refer to quick tricks quite often in this lesson. We are happy to open 2@C with a big hand, but only if it has 4 quick tricks. Of course there will be some other thoughts. I certainly am not saying you should open 2@C with all hands that have 4 quick tricks. That would be silly. But I am saying that you should not open 2@C with fewer than 4 quick tricks. Do you need a little review on quick tricks? |
PG| ***** 7 ***** |


NT||
