qx||ht|b|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|Fair enough. It is the number of tricks you take in each suit on the first 2 rounds. Period. So AKQJ is only 2 quick tricks. You can't have more than 2 quick tricks in one suit. |
PG| ***** 8 ***** |


AT|

Ace is one quick trick. KQ is one quick trick. You lead the king, they win the ace, and the queen wins the 2nd round. AQ is 1' quick tricks. Depending on which opponent has the K, you will either win 1 or 2 tricks in the first 2 rounds. So we use 1' as an average. King-small is a ' quick trick. Depending on who has the ace, you may or may not win the first or second round.|
PG| ***** 9 ***** |


AT|

Those are the only 5 combinations that you can use to count quick tricks. KQJ is not 2 quick tricks. The jack is never 'quick'. It may be useful as a slow trick but not as a quick trick. I count my quick tricks on every hand. It is very easy to do. Keep it in mind. There is a lot more to evaluating your hand than HCP. Hopefully you already know that.|
PG| ***** 10 ***** |


HT|l|cs|2|3d|5|at|^b  {|ih|pSS K Q T H A Q 9 D A K T 8 3 C K 5|at|}|lb|*yShould you open this hand 2C?^^y|ht|L|at|^K@2This hand has 21 HCP at first blush. I am afraid that plenty of bridge players would open 2NT. But that is incorrect. Not because this lesson is about opening 2@C. We will see strong hands where you should not open 2@C. But evaluating this hand as only 21 points in NT is wrong. Why do I love this hand? |
PG| ***** 12 ***** |


ht|r|at|^B@2The 5-card suit. I never saw one I didn't like. And this 5-card suit has 3 honors. Any suit with at least 3 honors and at least 4 cards is a 'quality suit'. That is the term I use. And you should always add 1 point to your hand when you are lucky enough to hold a quality suit. You won't get them as often as you would like. And you should also add 1 point for your 5-card suit. You don't get those on every hand either.|
PG| ***** 13 ***** |


AT|

So now we are up to 23 points. I am not saying the following results in adding any more points to this hand. But did you notice the intermediate cards? You have 4 intermediates ' the @S10, @H9, @D10, and @D8. Four intermediate cards is a nice number. There are many hands where you don't hold any tens, nines, or eights. |
PG| ***** 14 ***** |


