qx||ht|b|cs|2|3d|5|at|^b  {|ih|pSS K Q T H A Q 9 D A K T 8 3 C K 5|hc|skqhaqdakck5|at|}|ht|b|cp|8|AT|^k@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|Also worth noting is that we don't hold any jacks. Jacks are often useless, particularly in slams. How did we do in the quick trick department? 1 in spades (@SKQ), 1' in hearts (@HAQ), 2 in diamonds (@DAK), and ' in clubs (@CK5). That's a total of 5 quick tricks. You might spend many days before you see a hand with 5 quick tricks. That is a superb number. The bottom line is that this is a clear cut 2@C opener. It is a balanced hand.|
PG| ***** 15 ***** |


LC|skqhaqdakck5|
ht|h|at|^B@2So when partner responds 2@D, as they almost always will (we will get into that more later on), you will rebid 2NT. If partner has nothing, they will pass. Of course they could transfer to a major with a 5-card suit even with nothing. That would suit us just fine with our nice support for both majors. |
PG| ***** 16 ***** |


AT|

The single most important thing that you must do accurately in every auction is hand evaluation. And it is doable. You don't have to be an expert on squeezes to evaluate your hand sensibly. Use the guidelines that I have written about and hopefully you have learned. Many of my guidelines applied to this very upgradeable hand that is far too good to open 2NT.|
PG| ***** 17 ***** |


ht|n|cs|2|3d|5|at|^c  {|ih|pSS K Q J H K Q J D K Q J C K J 5 3|hc|skqhkqdkqckj|at|}|lb|*yShould you open this hand 2C?^^n|at|}|ht|n|va|3|cp|8|AT|^l@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|In a word, yuck! 'But Marty, you have 22 HCP. That's a lot.' Don't get me wrong. I am not saying this is a weak hand. But of all the hands in the world with 22 technical HCP, this hand is about as bad as it could be. Note no aces. No intermediates. That is never good. How about quick tricks? One each in spades, hearts, and diamonds and only ' in clubs. Only 3' quick tricks. I am not opening 2@C. Not to mention look at the 4 jacks.|
PG| ***** 19 ***** |


lc|skqhkqdkqckj|ht|t|at|^B@2They are not worth 4 points. Just like with 4 aces, I hope you would not think that is only 16 HCP. Aces are worth more than 4 points and jacks are worth less than 1 HCP. You also have 3 queens. They are not worth 2 points each. Last but not least, 4-3-3-3 distribution. That is the worst distribution you can have. |
PG| ***** 20 ***** |


AT|

This hand is not worth 22 HCP. Ultimately bridge is all about taking tricks. At the end of the hand all you care about is how many tricks you have taken. The number of HCP you had is no longer relevant. So with this pile of garbage (admittedly a big pile) I am opening 2NT. I am not opening 2@C. I don't like this hand even a little bit.|
